e);\\n    }\\n\\n    private static void assertBundleContainsExpectedMessage(ResourceBundle bundle) {\\n        assertNotNull(bundle);\\n        assertEquals(PROPERTIES_NAME_IS_NULL_OR_EMPTY, bundle.getString(\\\"0028\\\"));\\n    }\\n}\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1777918725607}}\n/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge1/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/logs/org.hsqldb:hsqldb:2.4.1/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-04T18-12-23-075336Z.log:1825:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering native image behavior**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether a native image treats static final variables as constants. If a method isn't a compile-time constant and instead gets initialized at runtime, it complicates things. The initialization for a library in a native image might occur at build-time. Changing something may not impact the compiled branch if it’s constant-folded. But then, if the class is initialized at image build, maybe newGetBundleMethod is a non-null constant. And do HSQLDB classes initialize at runtime by default? It might be a mix of both, right?\\n\\n**Evaluating Java imports**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how to handle imports in Java. It seems common that I should avoid using qualified names and just go for something straightforward, like `sun.misc.Unsafe`. But wait, I wonder if Checkstyle will flag that as an internal issue? I should probably check if there are any existing tests using this. It's crucial to ensure everything aligns for best practices while coding. Let's keep this in mind moving forward!\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0eda5157bc4a7c690169f8e2ddd278819c8d83a2375e3eab8f\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp-OMF6IA0uQBL8N1Obh6v9BkX2T5jpc2rJ8A-Mw-h0e0HZbCAi8TLW9F4vIYUQyK0tHheT7yjAaJVMTC7rshgoSak_9DuNQIDnrKSYaHcM0F0niOORlnoGQUkXmegaW5Q-1pfPSaKHUJnQ1lg4_M1nTfCMQnuUQvV65sRRscnbFSz08YGhglcIeR2Cd